Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. 09:21 AM; Case called for Hearing.  Defendant Walter D Zweck in court, in custody at WCJ.  Andrew Nesheim appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Court reviews the case and inquires if the defendant is able to post bail in both matters. Defendant advises he is not able to post bail.  Defendant presents additional statements with regards to why he did not make his last court appearance, and is asking to have his bail amount lowered.  Court notes the defendant was previously represented by the Public Defender's office.  Defendant confirms he would be eligible.  State advises that he has no proof the defendant was incustody during the last  missed court appearance and notes the defendant has missed more than 1 hearing.  Court will adjourn for status if counsel next week and have the clerk's office contact the PD's office to make sure they have someone appointed.  Hearing scheduled for May 18, 2022 at 02:30 pm.
